Mask-usage recognition with Machine learning.¶

Introduction

The following exercise has the purpose of using Machine Learning to identify the usage of masks in different images of people.

With the ongoing situation of the Covid pandemic the usage of masks took an important role in the fight against the transmission of the virus. Using the Worlds Health Organization words:

Masks are a key measure to suppress transmission and save lives.1

The idea is to use a machine learning library and model to identify if a person is wearing or not a mask; exploring the capabilities of machine learning.

For this exercise I used TensorFlow, the open-source library for machine learning; and the datasets used for training and testing were taken from Kaggle.2 Without further due, lets jump right in to the exercise.

Imports.

The first thing to do is to import all the necessary libraries.

Preprocessing.

To be able to feed the model with data, it has to be preprocessed first. This means that the data has to be in the right format; in this case the data will transformed from an image to a tensor so the model can read and work with it.

Build the model¶

Now that the data is prepared to be used for training, it is time to build the model. With a standard approach, the model will consist of convolutional layers with relu as their activation function, it will also have basic set of Pooling layers and a final flatten layer. But why convolutional layers? Convolutional layers are the right approach because:

[It] is the simple application of a filter to an input that results in an activation. Repeated application of the same filter to an input results in a map of activations called a feature map, indicating the locations and strength of a detected feature in an input, such as an image. 3

In [ ]:
num_classes = 3

model = Sequential([
  layers.experimental.preprocessing.Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=(128, 128, 3)),
  layers.Conv2D(16, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Conv2D(32, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Conv2D(64, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Flatten(),
  layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
  layers.Dense(num_classes)
])

Compile the model

After we build the model its necessary to compile and select the hyperparameters (optimizers and loss function) that will guide and adjust the model to be able to learn from the training set.

In [ ]:
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

We can have a reference on how the model is performing during each epoch of training thanks to the validation set which can compared with the training set. The performance is measured with two metrics: accuracy and the result of the loss function for each epoch.

Seeing the accuracy results it appears that the model is not overfitted (yet) as it provided a high accuracy for the validation data set. It is also possible to note that with every epoch the accuracy increases in the training dataset. This means the training is capable of adjusting its parameters for learning better. However it could also mean that the adjustment could be adapting to the samples too much.

Regarding the results of the loss function for the training set and the validation set, it also seems to be a good result. The loss function decreases drastically in the first epochs, which shows the model is reducing the difference between the prediction and the actual result. However it is also showing signs of overfitting; the loss function keeps drecreasing for the training samples, but for the validation samples it has spikes showing a higher loss function, which means the parameters are adjusting mainly for the training samples.

Nevertheless it is still important to see the model perform in new data (the test dataset)

In [ ]:
acc = history.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']

loss = history.history['loss']
val_loss = history.history['val_loss']

epochs_range = range(epochs)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(epochs_range, acc, label='Training Accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs_range, val_acc, label='Validation Accuracy')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(epochs_range, loss, label='Training Loss')
plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label='Validation Loss')
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
plt.show()

Its important to note that the model has not suffered major or minor changes from its initial setting. Definitely the power of keras, Tensorflow and machine learning in general can be seen here; without further tuning, it seems the model does a pretty good job classifying images of people wearing masks, wearing them incorrectly or not wearing them at all.

Testing the model with new data¶

One way to see how the model performs on new data (data that was not used for training nor validation) is by simply calling the evaluate method on the test dataset. This method measures the loss function and the accuracy of all the samples in the test dataset, giving a good reference of how is the model performing

In [ ]:
test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(testdata)

65/65 [==============================] - 15s 216ms/step - loss: 0.3160 - accuracy: 0.9252

The model predicted correctly 92.52% of the samples.

The performance wasn't as good as the one with the training or validation samples, which means overfitting. Nonetheless the model still has a high accuracy, making it useful for prediction.

Exploring results.¶

Despite the model evaluation provided a good result, it is also a good idea to see it in action next to the actual images that are used for prediction.

In [ ]:
num_image= ["first image", "second image", "third image", "fourth image"]

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
for images, labels in testdata.take(1):
  for i in range(4):
    ax = plt.subplot(2, 2, i + 1)
    
    plt.imshow(images[i].numpy().astype("uint8"))
    plt.title(class_names2[labels[i]])
    plt.axis("off")

    img_array = keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(images[i])
    img_array = tf.expand_dims(img_array, 0) # Create a batch

    predictions = model.predict(img_array)
    score = tf.nn.softmax(predictions[0])
    print(
    "The {} most likely belongs to {} with a {:.2f} percent confidence."
    .format(num_image[i], class_names[np.argmax(score)], 100 * np.max(score)))

Conclusion¶

This was a simple exercise to explore machine learning and Tensorflow capabilities. It was possible to see that convolutional networks are a great option for image classification; In this exercise a basic convolutional model was built with an accuracy over 90% classifying images into three categories. Not only the ideas and theory behind Machine learning are effective but also the tools to apply those ideas are powerful enough to find useful and interesting applications. Definitely in a production environment more aspects should be considered, but the foundation for the use of data and machine learning is set and ready to be exploited.
